# Load the GeoDataFrame containing United States geometry shapes (at a state-level):
state_shapes = "https://github.com/babdelfa/gis/blob/main/state_geometry.zip?raw=true"
with fsspec.open(state_shapes) as states_file:
    state_shapes = gpd.read_file(states_file)
    
# Load the GeoDataFrame containing United States geometry shapes (at a county-level):

    county_shapes = gpd.read_file(counties_file)

# Identify the top 5 counties with the highest cumulative COVID-19 case counts and display their totals.

#I renamed admin2 to county so it is easier to call later when I need it
df.rename(columns={"Admin2" : "County"}, inplace=True)

#since the last column is the cumulative cases count, I am storing this as a value so I can call it later
lastCol = df.columns[-1]

#I made a new df that only includes the top 5 counties by sorting the values based on the last column in the original df
top5 = df[['County', lastCol]]
top5 = top5.sort_values(by=lastCol, ascending=False)
#I renamed the second column to total cases so it is easier to call later
top5.rename(columns={top5.columns[1]: 'Total_cases'}, inplace=True)
top5 = top5.head(5)
top5

# Display the results in a clear, readable format with the county name and corresponding 'Day 0' date.

#this sorts the df so that it sorts the top 5 counties at the top
top5_sorted = df.sort_values(by=lastCol, ascending=False).head(5)

#here I am iterating through the dates rows to find the first value greater than 0 and adding it to a new list called dayZero
dayZero = []
for index, row in top5_sorted.iterrows():
    # the row[8:] is the columns that are the dates only
    for col, value in row[8:].items():
        if value > 0:
            dayZero.append(col)
            break
# code to get the names of the counties
county_names=[]
for county in top5_sorted['County']:
    county_names.append(county)
# This prints the indexes that match the other list and prints the results
for county, date in zip(county_names, dayZero):
    print(county,':', date)

# Create a line plot to visualize trends in cumulative COVID-19 cases for the top 5 counties over time. 
# Display the cumulative case counts for all five counties on the same chart.

#first I made a new df that contains only the county names and all the dates
# I converted this into a vertical data frame using melt so that it is easier to plot the points
dates = top5_sorted.columns[8:]
newDF = top5_sorted[['County'] + list(dates)]
counties_melt = pd.melt(newDF, id_vars = ['County'], var_name = 'Dates')
# this allows the dates to be turned from string to datetime which i can use to plot
counties_melt['Dates'] = pd.to_datetime(counties_melt['Dates'])

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.lineplot(data=counties_melt, x='Dates', y='value', hue='County')
plt.title('Top 5 Counties with Highest Cumulative COVID-19 Cases Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Cases')
plt.xticks(rotation=50) 
plt.legend(title='County')
plt.show()

# Create an interactive choropleth map highlighting the top 5 counties with the highest cumulative COVID-19 case counts.
# Configure popups to display each county's name, state, and cumulative case count (nothing else).
# Limit popups on the map to these top five counties.

# merging the county shapes with the sorted top 5 data to use for the map.
#using FIPS to merge the two tables
merged_county = pd.merge(county_shapes, top5_sorted, left_on='FIPS_BEA', right_on='FIPS')

#create the map
map_county = folium.Map(location=[40, -95], zoom_start=4)

# this is code that is needed to fill out the map using the merged data
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=merged_county,
    data=merged_county,
    columns=['FIPS_BEA', lastCol],
    key_on='feature.properties.FIPS_BEA',
    fill_color='YlOrRd',
    fill_opacity=0.8,
    line_opacity=1,
    legend_name='Cumulative COVID-19 Cases',
).add_to(map_county)

    columns=['STATE_NAME', lastCol],
    key_on='feature.properties.STATE_NAME',  
    fill_color='OrRd',  
    fill_opacity=0.8,
    line_opacity=1,
    legend_name='Cumulative COVID-19 Cases'
).add_to(map_states)

# Create a 2x2 grid of subplots and include the two line plots and two bar plots from above.
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15, 10))

#county bar graph
axes[0, 0].bar(top5_sorted['County'], top5_sorted[lastCol])
axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('County')
axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Cases')
axes[0, 0].set_title('Top 5 Counties with Highest Cumulative COVID-19 Cases')

#county line plot
sns.lineplot(data=counties_melt, x='Dates', y='value', hue='County', ax=axes[0, 1])
axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Date')
axes[0, 1].set_ylabel('Cases')
axes[0, 1].set_title('Top 5 Counties with Highest Cumulative COVID-19 Cases Over Time')

#state bar graph
axes[1, 0].bar(top5_sorted['Province_State'], top5_sorted[lastCol], color='green')
axes[1, 0].set_xlabel('State')
axes[1, 0].set_ylabel('Cases')
axes[1, 0].set_title('Top 5 States with Highest Cumulative COVID-19 Cases')

#state line plot
sns.lineplot(data=states_melt, x='Dates', y='value', hue='Province_State', ax=axes[1, 1])
axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Date')
axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('Cases')
axes[1, 1].set_title('Top 5 States with Highest Cumulative COVID-19 Cases Over Time')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
